W. T. G. They set their burdens down . 
Larry looked at them with interest . 
You surely have those things well trained , Lakla , he said . 
Things ! The handmaiden arose , eyes flashing with indig nation . 
You call my Akka things ! Well , said Larry , a bit taken aback , what do you call them ? My Akka are a PEOPLE , she retorted . 
As much a people as your race or mine . 
They are good and loyal , and they have speech and arts , and they slay not , save for food or to pro tect themselves . 
And I think them beautiful , Larry , BEAUTIFUL ! She stamped her foot . 
And you call them THINGS ! Beautiful ! These ? Yet , after all , they were , in their gro tesque fashion . 
And to Lakla , surrounded by them , from babyhood , they were not strange , at all . 
Why shouldn't she think them beautiful ? The same thought must have struck O'Keefe , for he flushed guiltily . 
I think them beautiful , too , Lakla , he said remorsefully . 
It's my not knowing your tongue too well that traps me . 
TRULY , I think them beautiful I'd tell them so , if I knew their talk . 
